titlestmt.titleproper: A Guide to the Rockefeller Foundation records, projects, SG 1.9-SG 1.13 (A83-A87) FA479

did.langmaterial: Multiple languages contained in written material specific to country/region. Predominately written in English.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Records have received basic level 1 processing to establish initial intellectual and physical control of the holdings. Materials remain in original record cartons and folders.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.
For material arranged by Program, the File title provides an alphanumeric representing the Program code letters and grant number, followed by file description.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Reccords are primarily arranged by Program.
Some subgroups may contain portions of the material that are arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Project files transferred to the RAC by Rockefeller Foundation, 1983-1987.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Foundation was established by act of the New York State Legislature approved by the Governor on May 14, 1913, "to promote the well-being of mankind throughout the world." Between 1913 and 1928 the China Medical Board, the International Health Board, and the Division of Medical Education functioned as divisions of the Foundation, concentrating on the administration of programs in public health and medical education. A Division of Studies was created in 1923 to handle projects outside the medical field. These early years were experimental as the new foundation studied the methods of philanthropy and explored its relationships with other Rockefeller boards. Although the Rockefeller Foundation is the largest and best known philanthropy founded by the Rockefeller family, it was neither the first nor the last to be established. The Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research (1901), the General Education Board (1902), the Rockefeller Sanitary Commission for the Eradication of Hookworm Disease (1909), and the Bureau of Social Hygiene (1911) all existed earlier. When the Foundation was created, the Sanitary Commission was disbanded. After the establishment of the Foundation, the Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial (1918) and the International Education Board (1923) were created.

The Rockefeller boards and their programs were reconsidered and reorganized in 1927-1928 in order to avoid overlapping programs. The International Health Board of the Foundation was disbanded and an International Health Division was organized. The China Medical Board, Inc., was established as a separately incorporated institution, and the China Medical Board of the Foundation ceased to exist. The Division of Studies was dropped and the Division of Medical Education was phased out. The Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial was combined with the Foundation and the Spelman Fund of New York was chartered to continue activities of the LSRM that were not absorbed by the Foundation. The International Education Board was disbanded.

As a result of this reorganization, the Foundation adopted a program which included public health work (administered by the IHD), the advancement of knowledge in the medical and natural sciences (in part taken over from the IEB), the social sciences (formerly the field of the LSRM), and the humanities and arts (shared with the GEB). The Rockefeller Institute and the Bureau of Social Hygiene were not affected by the reorganization. The program adopted by the Foundation at this time remained basically the same for the next twenty years.

As its files accumulated, the Foundation maintained a card index recording the names of institutional and individual grantees and correspondents. A microfilm copy of this index is available at the Archive Center.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation note
prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use note
userestrict.p: Rockefeller Foundation retains title, copyright and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Records more than 20 years old are open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Types of records include: project and fellowship material.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Files transferred to RAC by the Rockefeller Foundation, 1984.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Records have received basic level 1 processing to establish initial intellectual and physical control of the holdings. Materials remain in original record cartons and folders.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

did.unittitle: Brazil - University Development - Education for Development Program

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: General background on university development in Brazil: i.e. diaries of team visits; overall prospects of RF support; evaluations of progress; Velasquez correspondence (to and from New York) on EFD planning; correspondence with university officials about team visits and RF funding; correspondence and memoranda about overall planning, development and administration of PROPED (program of research and education for development) ; official letters of request and RF notification of allocations for PROPED support.

Agricultural Sciences (A 84) ‚Äî Correspondence and memoranda about AS interests in EFD program; input on development of agronomy faculty at Cruz das Almas. Correspondence to and from Jim Maner, Susan Almy (rural development), Kenneth Buhr and Eugenio Martiner. Diaries of JA Pino visits.

Health Sciences (A 84) ‚Äî Correspondence about development of rural and community health projects and Center for the Study of Regional Diseases. Correspondence to and from Willoughby Lathem, Stephen Plank, James Olson. Lathem periodic reports. VC Scott and GS Hayes (NY officers) diaries of visits.

Social Sciences (A 84) ‚Äî Correspondence and memoranda about the development of a graduate training program of economics and socio-anthropological studies; correspondence and memos and diaries from A Musalem and Fuenzilidia. Diaries of S Almy. Correspondence and reports on micro economic studies and small business enterprise.

Administration (A 84) ‚Äî Correspondence and memoranda on local office administration and administrative matters concerning operations of EFD program center: i.e. routine correspondence about team visits; budget matters; office and vehicle matters; routine personnel matters; fellowship award administration.
Administration Housing (A 84) ‚Äî Correspondence, memoranda concerning the purchase or rental of housing for staff assigned to Brazil EFD, including correspondence re utilities and furnishings.
Agreement (NY) ‚Äî Correspondence, memoranda and agreements re RF participation in an EFD program in Brazil; privileges extended RF staff by Brazilian government.
Program Review (A 82) ‚Äî Program reviews (1974, 1979) by RF officers and 1979 reviews by outside evaluators Sheldon M. Wolff, Arnold C. Harberger and Eduardo L. Venezian.
Staff Minutes (A 84) ‚Äî Minutes of meetings held by RF Bahia staff, August 14, 1974 through November 9, 1977

- General background on university development in Indonesia

- Correspondence re RF policy on visiting faculty and personnel assigned to GMU
- Correspondence from A.J. Nyberg re development at GMU
- Correspondence re external assistance (non RF) to GMU
- Correspondence re overall faculty development at GMU; overall library development; overall evaluations of allocations; personnel assigned to GMU
- Program review documents

- Final report "EFD - cooperative program, GMU and RF, 1971-83
Administration

- Correspondence and memoranda on administrative matters concerning the operation of the EFD program center office, i.e. routine correspondence about officer and team visits (itineraries, travel arrangements, appointments) - to and from RF representative, A.J. Nyberg, and acting representative, R. Northrup
- Correspondence and notification about bank deposits; audits; budgets and accountings: charges to local EFD center budget (see Note 1 below)
- Personnel policies for local staff
- Correspondence about starting at English speaking school in Yogykarta
- Correspondence with field staff concerning articles and books which are of interest to them
- Correspondence about the purchase of books and journals for RF staff members
Note: 1) Correspondence and memoranda related to and charged to items shown in EFD center budget (attached) should be filed in 652 UD - Administration, with the exception of cars and housing.
2) Correspondence re housing: SEE 652 UD - Gadjah Mada University - Staff Housing
3) Correspondence re autos: SEE 652 UD - Administration - Automobiles
Administration Automobiles
- Correspondence, memoranda concerning purchase and shipment of vehicles for RF staff assigned to GMU
Agreement
- Correspondence, memoranda concerning RF agreement with Government of the Republic of Indonesia
Agricultural Sciences
- Correspondence and memoranda about AS interests at GMU; with AS field staff assigned to GMU. Correspondence dealing with the establishment and maintenance of relationships with agro complex at GMU
- General correspondence about RF agricultural sciences fellows from GMU
- Diaries of RF staff assigned to GMU (Tillman and Thompson, Crowder and Warwick)
- Reports and papers on AS subjects in relation to curriculum development
- Occasional "situation" reports vis a vis agro complex at GMU
- Report by Tillman (December 1980) of seven year experience in EFD at GMU
Medical Sciences (or Health Sciences)
- Correspondence, memoranda and diaries of Lucien Gregg and Joe Wray concerning possibilities for an RF role in medicine and health related areas at GMU
- Correspondence re development of a medical team at GMU
- Reports of consultants assigned to investigate medical and health departments and facilities at GMU
- Correspondence and memoranda to and from Jon Rohde and Robert Northrup on medical and health related issues, programs and policies
- Sundry mimeographed project studies on comprehensive community health, population studies, child health
Social Sciences
- Diaries of K.W. Thompson and social science officers concerning an SS role at GMU
- Correspondence and memoranda to and from D. Hedley and C. MacAndrews on general social science related issues, programs and policies
- Because of A.J. Nyberg's role as RF representative and economics professor at GMU, 652 UD and 652 UD - Administration should also be consulted for possible social science related correspondence
- Diaries of D. Hedley and C. MacAndrews
Allocations and Fellows
Individual files are maintained for each allocation (see 652 UD - Minutes for mark up) and for each Indonesian fellow (652 E)

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Files transferred to the RAC by Rockefeller Foundation, 1985.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Records have received basic level 1 processing to establish initial intellectual and physical control of the holdings. Materials remain in original record cartons and folders.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Files transferred to the RAC by Rockefeller Foundation, 1986.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Records have received basic level 1 processing to establish initial intellectual and physical control of the holdings. Materials remain in original record cartons and folders.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Files transferred to the RAC by Rockefeller Foundation, 1987.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Records have received basic level 1 processing to establish initial intellectual and physical control of the holdings. Materials remain in original record cartons and folders.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.
